The paper deals with the competition complexity of auction settings, which is a topic in algorithmic game theory (cs.GT). The paper also involves analyzing the revenue of different auction mechanisms, which falls under the category of mechanism design (cs.DS). The use of stochastic dominance and random variables suggests a connection to probability and statistics (cs.PR or cs.ST), but since the focus is on auction theory, we prioritize the other categories. The paper also involves analyzing the performance of auction mechanisms for different types of valuations, which is a common theme in artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and computational economics (cs.EC). Finally, the paper involves analyzing the complexity of the auction setting as the number of bidders and items increase, which suggests a connection to information theory (cs.IT).
